         <ce:floats>
            <ce:figure id="f0005">
               <ce:label>Fig. 1</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0005">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0015" view="all">The (a) boundary of Utah Forest Dynamics Plot, UT, USA and the locations of all mapped <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings. (b) A <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> seedling growing from the surface near the catface of a mature heterospecific. (c) A <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> sapling (DBH &lt; 1.0 cm) with seven cones. (d) A <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedling growing on rocky substrate. (e) A <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> seedling rooted underneath <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> deadwood. (f) A <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedling growing in a patch of graminoids.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr1" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0378112723002839/gr1" id="lk00005"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0010">
               <ce:label>Fig. 2</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0010">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0020" view="all">Distribution of diameter at breast height (DBH) and basal diameter for <ce:italic>Pinus flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>Pinus longaeva</ce:italic> at the Utah Forest Dynamics Plot, UT, USA. Dashed lines denote the quartiles (25th–75th) of each distribution. (a) The DBH distribution for the entire populations. (b) The DBH distribution from 1 to 10 cm. (c) The basal diameter distribution of all seedlings.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr2" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0378112723002839/gr2" id="lk00010"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0015">
               <ce:label>Fig. 3</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0015">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0025" view="all">The spatial patterns for seedlings of <ce:italic>Pinus flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>Pinus longaeva</ce:italic> at the Utah Forest Dynamics Plot, UT, USA. Values above (below) the shaded confidence values are more aggregated (dispersed) than expected under spatial randomness. All patterns were tested from 0 to 10.0 m at intervals of 0.25 m. (a) The aggregation of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> seedlings. (b) The aggregation of <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings. (c) The aggregation of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> seedlings around <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> adults. (d) The aggregation of <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings around <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> adults. (e) The aggregation of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> seedlings around <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> adults. (f) The aggregation of <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings around <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> adults. (g) The aggregation of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> seedlings around deadwood. (h) The aggregation of <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings around deadwood. (i) The aggregation of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> adults around deadwood. (j) The aggregation of <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> adults around deadwood. (k) The difference in aggregation around deadwood between <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> seedlings and adults. (l) The difference in aggregation around deadwood between <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings and adults.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr3" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0378112723002839/gr3" id="lk00015"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0020">
               <ce:label>Fig. 4</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0020">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0030" view="all">The radial distribution of (a) <ce:italic>Pinus flexilis</ce:italic> and (b) <ce:italic>Pinus longaeva</ce:italic> within 2.0 m of mapped deadwood at the Utah Forest Dynamics Plot, Utah, USA. Seedling distributions are plotted in 10 cm distance increments around each coarse woody debris according to their categorical orientation around each coarse woody debris.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr4" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0378112723002839/gr4" id="lk00020"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0025">
               <ce:label>Fig. 5</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0025">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0035" view="all">The output of habitat models for seedlings (a:b) and adults (c:d) of (a, c) <ce:italic>Pinus flexilis</ce:italic> and (b, d) <ce:italic>Pinus longaeva</ce:italic> at the Utah Forest Dynamics Plot. Variables were tested as predictors in a Random Forest habitat model and are plotted in decreasing order of the mean decrease in the GINI coefficient for each species. Higher values indicate more importance in the variable for explaining seedling occurrence. The variables tested were: the distance to the nearest mature <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> (<ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic>), the distance to the nearest mature <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> (<ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic>), the distance to the nearest deadwood (deadwood), the diameter of deadwood (Size), the distance to the nearest non-<ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic> tree (Non-<ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic>), the elevation, the topographic wetness index (TWI), the calcium content of the soil (Ca), the pH of the soil (pH), the potassium content of the soil (K), the manganese content of the soil (Mn), the ammonium content of the soil (Am), the McCune Heat Index (McCune), and the canopy cover (Cover).</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr5" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0378112723002839/gr5" id="lk00025"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0030">
               <ce:label>Fig. 6</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0030">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0040" view="all">The distribution of coarse woody debris, by tree species and decay classification, at the Utah Forest Dynamics Plot, Utah, USA. All coarse woody debris (≥10 cm diameter at large end) was mapped and classified into decay classifications (<ce:cross-ref id="opto4jL6KVCGO" refid="bib337">Harmon et al., 2008</ce:cross-ref>), and when possible, identified to species or genus.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr6" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0378112723002839/gr6" id="lk00030"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:figure id="f0035">
               <ce:label>Fig. 7</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0035">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0045" view="all">The distribution of each tree species population by elevation at the Utah Forest Dynamics Plot, UT, USA. Adult and seedling populations of <ce:italic>Pinus flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>Pinus longaeva</ce:italic> are plotted separately from all other tree species. The area under each curve sums to 1.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
               <ce:link locator="gr7" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/23.4" xlink:href="pii:S0378112723002839/gr7" id="lk00035"/>
            </ce:figure>
            <ce:table xmlns="http://www.elsevier.com/xml/common/cals/dtd" frame="topbot" id="t0005" rowsep="0" colsep="0">
               <ce:label>Table 1</ce:label>
               <ce:caption id="cn0040">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0050" view="all">The habitat characteristics tested in a habitat model and their median values for seedling <ce:italic>Pinus flexilis</ce:italic> (n = 1,052) and <ce:italic>Pinus longaeva</ce:italic> (n = 498) at the Utah Forest Dynamics Plot, Utah, USA. Standard deviations are provided in parenthesis. Significant differences are indicated in bold. Different superscript letters indicate significant (p &lt; 0.05) differences between seedling species.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:caption>
