            <ce:abstract class="author" id="ab010" view="all"><ce:abstract-sec id="as010" view="all">
                  <ce:simple-para id="sp0010" view="all">The spatial patterns of trees are a defining feature of forests, yet because of the long lifespan of trees, the full origins of these spatial patterns remain unclear. We used 15.6 ha of a mapped forest plot to assess the local habitat characteristics and spatial structure of 1,550 naturally established seedlings and 1,955 adults of <ce:italic>Pinus flexilis</ce:italic> (limber pine) and <ce:italic>Pinus longaeva</ce:italic> (Great Basin bristlecone pine) in southern Utah, USA. For both species, proximity to deadwood (large end diameter ≥ 10 cm) and mature trees were key parameters of habitat, likely indicating abiotic or biotic facilitation. Both seedlings and mature trees were highly aggregated 0.0–2.5 m around large pieces of deadwood, which can persist in this ecosystem for centuries or millennia. Seedlings were most often located around deadwood 15–22 cm in diameter, though deadwood size had little influence on the distance at which seedlings established. Seedlings of both <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> were abundant near heterospecific adult <ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic>. The elevational distribution of seedlings and adults of both species were not different, indicating a regeneration niche similar to the niche of mature trees and also that changing climate at this site has not yet affected species distributions. Low amounts of manganese and higher levels of pH and potassium in the mineral soil were associated with <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings but were less important for <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic>. Edaphic patterns combined with the presence of deadwood define the overlap between seedling and mature species habitat and identify the key drivers influencing the spatial structure in this high-elevation, old-growth forest. Likely, persistence of these two <ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic> species as well as regeneration or site colonization is more favorable in the presence of large deadwood.</ce:simple-para>
               </ce:abstract-sec></ce:abstract>
            <ce:keywords class="keyword" id="kg005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="st015">Keywords</ce:section-title>
               <ce:keyword id="k0005">
                  <ce:text>Great basin bristlecone pine</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0010">
                  <ce:text>Limber pine</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0015">
                  <ce:text>Seedling recruitment</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0020">
                  <ce:text>Spatial statistics</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0025">
                  <ce:text>Smithsonian ForestGEO</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
               <ce:keyword id="k0030">
                  <ce:text>Utah forest dynamics plot</ce:text>
               </ce:keyword>
            </ce:keywords>
            <ce:data-availability id="da005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="st020">Data availability</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0025" view="all">Data is archived with the Smithsonian institution at https://forestgeo.si.edu.</ce:para>
            </ce:data-availability>
         </head>
         <body view="all">
            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="s0005" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st025">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0030" view="all">The long lifespan of trees obscures the originating processes that initiate their spatial distribution and its changes through time. Do spatial patterns of trees in high-elevation forests arise, <ce:italic>ab initio</ce:italic>, from dispersal processes, seedling germination and microsite facilitation (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0030" id="c0010">Baumeister and Calloway 2006</ce:cross-ref>)? Or do they arise primarily from competitive interactions among seedlings and saplings (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0175" id="c0015">Kenkel 1988</ce:cross-ref>)? Or, in forests with very long-lived individuals, do patterns in late seral forests arise from density-independent interactions far removed from seedling dynamics (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0200 b0225" id="r0005">Larson et al. 2015, Lutz et al. 2014</ce:cross-refs>)?</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">In western North America, high-elevation forests feature few tree species, but are usually characterized by at least one representative of the five-needle white pines (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0110" id="c0020">Eckert and Hall 2006</ce:cross-ref>). Populations of these species face considerable challenges from changing climate and the concomitant encroachment of bark beetles as well as the spread of non-native pathogens (<ce:italic>Cronartium ribicola,</ce:italic> white pine blister rust; <ce:cross-ref refid="b0185" id="c0025">Kinloch Jr. 2003</ce:cross-ref>). In Utah, the representative five-needle pines are <ce:italic>Pinus longaeva</ce:italic> D. K. Bailey (Great Basin bristlecone pine) and <ce:italic>Pinus flexilis</ce:italic> E. James (limber pine), both adapted to harsh, sub-alpine systems where their tolerance of cold temperatures, alkaline soil, and little summer precipitation allow them avoid other tree species (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0320" id="c0030">Tomback et al. 2010</ce:cross-ref>). Declines in <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> could cause substantial loss of ecosystem function as both pines can act as keystone and foundation species (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0120 b0320" id="r0010">Ellison et al. 2019, Tomback et al. 2010</ce:cross-refs>). With mortality of mature trees occurring in many stands (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0290" id="c0035">Schwandt et al. 2010</ce:cross-ref>), understanding the levels of recruitment and their spatial patterns may help guide the preservation of these foundational and keystone species on the landscape.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">Appropriate habitat for tree seedlings often represents a narrow range of conditions possessing both adequate resources and protection from potential mortality agents, such as desiccation, excessive snowpack, or mechanical damage. Particularly among trees that persist in harsh environments, the regeneration niche may be considerably more restricted than the adult niche (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0140 b0260" id="r0015">Grubb 1977, Poorter 2007</ce:cross-refs>). In that case, those seedlings that occupy favorable microsites may persist throughout forest development and the initial spatial pattern of seedlings would be similar to the pattern of adult trees. These microsites may be defined by land surface microtopography and its effects on snowpack and sunlight (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0145" id="c0040">Hankin et al. 2021</ce:cross-ref>) or by the presence of adult trees, shrubs, or deadwood that ameliorate the environment (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0075 b0030 b0240" id="r0020">Connell and Slayter 1977, Baumeister and Calloway 2006, Maher et al. 2015</ce:cross-refs>). In sufficiently harsh conditions, the presence of deadwood, which covers more forest surface area than either standing trees or snags may provide a dominant mechanism of mechanical facilitation. Seeds of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> are dispersed by Clark’s nutcracker (<ce:italic>Nucifraga columbiana</ce:italic>), rodents, and directly via gravity or wind (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0190" id="c0045">Lanner et al. 1988</ce:cross-ref>: <ce:cross-ref refid="b0315" id="c0050">Tomback 1980</ce:cross-ref>). Caching by <ce:italic>N. columbiana</ce:italic> of <ce:italic>Pinus albicaulis</ce:italic> (whitebark pine) frequently involves aboveground caches with greater vegetative cover and within four meters of mature trees (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0220" id="c0055">Lorenz et al. 2011</ce:cross-ref>), though belowground caching of multiple seeds is also common (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0310" id="c0060">Tomback et al. 1978</ce:cross-ref>). This non-random dispersal mechanism of seeds may play a critical role in shaping long-term forest dynamics and mature forest structure.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">Tree seedlings may be particularly vulnerable to negative density dependent mortality from competition or pathogens (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0020 b0335 b0295" id="r0025">Bai et al. 2012; Yan et al. 2015; Smithers et al. 2021</ce:cross-refs>), mechanical damage owing to their small stature (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0195" id="c0065">Larson and Franklin 2010</ce:cross-ref>), or herbivory (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0240" id="c0070">Maher et al. 2015</ce:cross-ref>). Proximity to conspecific or heterospecific adult trees can sometimes provide an avenue for facilitation to seedlings by mitigating environmental stressors (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0065" id="c0075">Calder and St. Clair 2012</ce:cross-ref>), uplifting water (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0115" id="c0080">Egerton-Warbuton et al. 2007</ce:cross-ref>), or by providing mycorrhizal inoculum or possibly through access to a common mycorrhizal network (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0070 b0305" id="r0030">Cline et al. 2005, Teste et al. 2009</ce:cross-refs>). However, seedlings adjacent to adult trees may also have increased risks from pathogens such as <ce:italic>Armillaria ostoyae</ce:italic> (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0255 b0205 b0235" id="r0035">Packer and Clay 2000; Liang et al. 2016; Lutz, Unpublished</ce:cross-refs>), competition (<ce:cross-refs id="optvS3JF5NpCW" refid="b0035 bib336">Birch et al., 2019; Johnson et al., 2014</ce:cross-refs>) ), or mechanical damage from windthrow or self-pruning. Although proximity of seedlings to adults can increase seedling mortality through the presence of species-specific pathogens, in stressful environments, conspecific adult trees may subsidize seedlings with water and nutrients through shared mycorrhiza inoculum or a common mycorrhizal network (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0300 b0060" id="r0040">Teste and Simard 2008, Booth and Hoeksema 2010</ce:cross-refs>, but see <ce:cross-ref refid="b0170" id="c0090">Karst et al. 2023</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">Local abiotic or biotic features, such as deadwood, may be particularly important for seedling recruitment as they can ameliorate local conditions, shelter seedlings from herbivores, and provide a favorable microclimate (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0240" id="c0095">Maher et al. 2015</ce:cross-ref>). <ce:cross-ref refid="b0085" id="c0100">Coop and Schoettle (2009)</ce:cross-ref> found that <ce:italic>Pinus aristata</ce:italic> (Rocky Mountain bristlecone pine) and <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> in Colorado were frequently aggregated around deadwood and snags out to at least 50 cm distances, in a post-wildfire environment. However, forest dynamics often operate at much greater spatial scales, particularly for large, mature trees which can influence their environment at scales from 0 to 10 m or more (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0135 b0050" id="r0045">Furniss et al. 2017; Birch et al. 2023</ce:cross-refs>). Therefore, assessing patterns of aggregation or dispersion at large distances may reveal patterns of facilitation or competition that short-distance surveys cannot assess.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">In the high-elevation, discontinuous forests of Utah the ranges of <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> overlap and offer an opportunity to identify the habitat characteristics associated with new recruitment of seedlings of each pine species (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0005" id="c0105">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="f0005"/>) and the extent to which they overlap. To identify the habitat of <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> seedlings we used 15.6 ha of a mapped forest to identify the characteristics associated with 1,500 seedlings and 1,995 adults in a high-elevation forest in southern Utah. Specifically, we were interested in the following questions:<ce:list id="l0010">
                        <ce:list-item id="o0025">
                           <ce:label>1.</ce:label>
                           <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">How do the habitat characteristics of seedling and mature trees differ between and within species?</ce:para>
                        </ce:list-item>
                        <ce:list-item id="o0030">
                           <ce:label>2.</ce:label>
                           <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">To what extent do <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> seedlings establish around conspecific and heterospecific adults?</ce:para>
                        </ce:list-item>
                        <ce:list-item id="o0035">
                           <ce:label>3.</ce:label>
                           <ce:para id="p0070" view="all">To what spatial extent does deadwood facilitate establishment of <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic>?</ce:para>
                        </ce:list-item>
                     </ce:list>
                  </ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0010" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st030">Methods</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="s0015" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st035">Study location</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0075" view="all">The study site was the Utah Forest Dynamics Plot (UFDP), 15.6 ha of primary forest (of which, 13.6 ha analyzed here) located at 3,100 m elevation in Cedar Breaks National Monument, Utah, USA (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0005" id="c0110">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>a) (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0135" id="c0115">Furniss et al. 2017</ce:cross-ref>). The UFDP was established in 2014–2015 following the protocols of the Smithsonian Forest Global Earth Observatory (ForestGEO; <ce:cross-ref refid="b0090" id="c0120">Davies et al. 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Principal species include <ce:italic>Abies bifolia</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Populus tremuloides</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Picea engelmannii</ce:italic>, <ce:italic>Pinus flexilis</ce:italic>, and <ce:italic>Pinus longaeva</ce:italic> (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0135 b0055" id="r0050">Furniss et al. 2017, Bishop et al. 2019</ce:cross-refs>). All live and dead woody stems ≥ 1 cm diameter at breast height (DBH; 1.37 m) (n = 29,879) were mapped, tagged, measured, and identified to species. In addition to woody stems ≥ 1 cm DBH, all deadwood ≥ 10 cm at its large end (n = 5,310; (<ce:cross-refs id="opt1fv8UECFis" refid="b0165 b0230">Janík et al., 2018; Lutz et al., 2021</ce:cross-refs>) and all seedlings of genus <ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic> ≥ 2-years-old were mapped. Both arboreal and ground-dwelling rodents and <ce:italic>N. columbiana</ce:italic> collect <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seeds within the UFDP and have been observed caching within the study area.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0080" view="all">This UFDP spans an elevation of 3037–3169 m with a mean annual temperature of 3.9 °C and mean annual precipitation of 768 ± 119 mm, of which 506 ± 137 mm occurs as snow (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0250" id="c0130">NRCS 2023</ce:cross-ref>). Most soils are alkaline (pH 7.0 – 8.1) and are within the Mollisol (Argicryolls), and Inceptisol (Haplocryepts) orders with clay to clay-loam textures. The most recent fire was in 1802 and trees either regenerated naturally following patchy-high severity burning or survived the wildfire. Other disturbances include intermittent drought and growing-season frosts which can defoliate trees (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0045" id="c0135">Birch et al., 2022</ce:cross-ref>). There have been no recorded management actions within the UFDP, and there is as yet no evidence of <ce:italic>Cronartium ribicola,</ce:italic> (white pine blister rust).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0020" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st040">Field measurements</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0085" view="all">The UFDP has been censused annually (2015 – 2022) for changes in health for all 29,879 stems and seedlings, with the most recent full remeasurement in 2020. Tree-ring chronologies were developed for all dominant overstory species within the UFDP, including mature <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0010" id="c0140">Anderson-Teixeira et al. 2022</ce:cross-ref>). We differentiated ‘adult’ trees as those with ≥ 1.0 cm DBH. All trees with &lt; 1.0 cm DBH are considered ‘seedlings’ within the text. Though, saplings of both <ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic> spp<ce:italic>.</ce:italic> can occasionally produce mature cones at smaller sizes (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0005" id="c0145">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>c). All trees and seedlings that are newly dead (ex., no live foliage, ruptured or broken stem at base) undergo a thorough mortality examination to identify the abiotic and biotic factors associated with death. If seedlings cannot be located for two subsequent years they are assumed to have been removed via abiotic (erosion) or biotic (consumption) processes.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0090" view="all">Soil nutrients were sampled in the summer of 2018 following the collection and analysis methods of <ce:cross-ref refid="b0025" id="c0150">Baldeck et al. (2013)</ce:cross-ref>. Soil samples were taken from the uppermost 10 cm of mineral soil in an ordered grid (n = 43) approximately every 40 m within the Utah Forest Dynamics Plot (UFDP). Additional samples (n = 89) were placed randomly within the UFDP. Non-nitrogen nutrients were extracted using a Mehlich III solution and analyzed using an atomic emission-inductively coupled plasma (AE-ICP, Perkin Elmer Inc., Massachusetts, USA). Nitrogen was extracted as NH4 + and NO3– with a 2 M KCI solution and analyzed using an auto-analyzer (OI FS 3000, OI Analytical, College Station, TX, USA).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0025" view="all">
                     <ce:label>2.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st045">Analysis</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:section id="s0030" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.3.1</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st050">Calculation of edaphic metrics</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0095" view="all">We calculated elevation, topographic wetness, McCune Heat Index, and canopy cover for each tree and seedling using a 0.5 × 0.5 m LiDAR digital elevation model (DEM; <ce:cross-ref refid="b0325" id="c0155">United States Geologic Survey 2018</ce:cross-ref>). We used a Wilcoxon rank sum test with a false-discovery rate p-adjustment to assess differences in elevation between species, seedlings, and adult trees. To approximate the available soil moisture across the UFDP, we calculated a one-step topographic wetness index (TWI) using SAGA 8.2.0 (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0080" id="c0160">Conrad et al. 2015</ce:cross-ref>). The TWI models hydrologic flow on the landscape according to local contours with higher TWI values associated with wetter conditions. To estimate the relative heat experienced by all trees, we calculated the McCune Heat Load Index using spatialEco 1.3–7 (<ce:cross-ref id="opt1tEzBX4iW9" refid="b0125">Evans and Murphy, 2021</ce:cross-ref>). The heat-index ranges from 0 (coolest) to 1 (warmest) and accounts for the combined roles of aspect, slope, and solar radiation in altering surface temperature (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0245" id="c0165">McCune and Keon 2002</ce:cross-ref>). To calculate canopy height and cover we used lidR 4.0 (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0275" id="c0170">Roussel et al. 2020</ce:cross-ref>) to normalize and classify strata in the LiDAR DEM before importing it into the LAStools 220,107 program (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0160" id="c0175">Isenburg 2022</ce:cross-ref>) to calculate the minimum, mean, and maximum canopy height and cover within each 0.5 × 0.5 m pixel. Soil nutrients were interpolated following the methods of <ce:cross-ref refid="b0050" id="c0180">Birch et al. (2023)</ce:cross-ref> (<ce:cross-ref refid="t0005" id="c0185">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>
                           <ce:float-anchor refid="t0005"/>). We normalized each variable before krigging and back-transforming each nutrient to its original units for analysis.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0100" view="all">To calculate the distance and bearing of all seedlings, relative to deadwood, we used the ‘near’ function in ArcMap 10.8.1 (ESRI, Redlands, CA, USA). This represents the closest point to the seedling on the mapped deadwood polygon. To estimate the diameter of the deadwood polygon at the point closest to each seedling, we calculated the slope of the taper in diameter from large to small end, for each piece of deadwood:<ce:display>
                              <ce:formula id="e0005">
                                 <mml:math altimg="si1.svg">
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">Deadwoodtaper</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo linebreak="goodbreak">=</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mfrac>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">D</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">I</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">A</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">L</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">E</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:msub>
                                             <mml:mo>-</mml:mo>
                                             <mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">D</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">I</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">A</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">S</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">E</mml:mi>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                             </mml:msub>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">LEN</mml:mi>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                       </mml:mfrac>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:math>
                              </ce:formula>
                           </ce:display>
                        </ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0105" view="all">Where DIA<ce:inf loc="post">LE</ce:inf> is the diameter of the deadwood at the large end, DIA<ce:inf loc="post">SE</ce:inf> is the diameter of the deadwood at the small end, and LEN is the length of the deadwood. We then used the taper of each log to estimate the diameter at the point on the deadwood closest to the seedling. We assessed the relationship between seedling distance and deadwood diameter using a linear regression in base R.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0035" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.3.2</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st055">Spatial statistics</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0110" view="all">To identify patterns of facilitation and competition between seedlings and mature adults, we used the inhomogeneous pairwise correlation function (IPCF). The IPCF identifies patterns of aggregation and dispersion among trees by comparing them against patterns of complete spatial randomness. The bivariate-IPCF enables the comparison of seedlings against conspecific and heterospecific adults to assess if seedlings are more aggregated (indicating facilitation or facilitation-like processes) or dispersed (indicating competition or apparent competition) around adult trees. Before using the IPCF we assessed an inhomogeneous distribution of seedlings and adults using the ‘quadrat-count’ function in spatstat 2.3–4 (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0015" id="c0190">Baddeley et al. 2015</ce:cross-ref>). We generated confidence envelopes representing complete spatial randomness by using 2000 Monte Carlo simulations. Seedling spatial patterns that fell outside the confidence intervals represented a significant spatial pattern. We examined spatial patterns in 0.25 m intervals from 0.0 to 10 m, representing the expected full spatial extent of facilitation and competition among mature trees (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0135" id="c0195">Furniss et al. 2017</ce:cross-ref>). To assess differences in spatial patterns between point patterns (ex., seedlings vs. adults), we differenced the patterns between each pattern and used the minimum and maxima of the confidence envelopes to assess significant differences between patterns.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0115" view="all">After identifying the closest point of intersection for each deadwood polygon, we used the point patterns to assess 1) the patterns of seedling aggregation and dispersion around deadwood, and 2) the directionality of seedling arrangement around all deadwood. We used the point pattern of the nearest deadwood to calculate the IPCF for seedling aggregation around all logs following the methods above. We used the ‘ggwindrose’ in the climaemet 1.0.2 package (Hernangomez and Fernande-Aviles 2022) to plot the radial distribution of seedlings around deadwood. Additionally, we assessed the spatial distribution of adult <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> around deadwood. Finally, to determine if seedlings were differentially aggregated around deadwood relative to adult trees, we assessed the species-specific spatial pattern between seedlings and adult trees, including non-<ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic> trees with more than 200 individuals.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                     <ce:section id="s0040" view="all">
                        <ce:label>2.3.3</ce:label>
                        <ce:section-title id="st060">Habitat model</ce:section-title>
                        <ce:para id="p0120" view="all">We used a down-sampled random forest approach to identify the drivers of seedling and adult habitat suitability. Random forest is an analytical tool that can identify the relative importance of independent variables that are co-linear or non-normal. We ran separate models for <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings and adults using a combination of abiotic and biotic variables (<ce:cross-ref refid="t0005" id="c0200">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>) selected based on <ce:italic>a priori</ce:italic> hypotheses of variables known to alter seedling survival (<ce:cross-ref refid="s0105" id="c0205">Table S1</ce:cross-ref>). We followed the recommendations and code of <ce:cross-ref refid="b0330" id="c0210">Valavi et al. (2021)</ce:cross-ref> for implementing a down-sampled model that mitigates error by subsampling random points in the study area. We used the ‘randomForest’ function in randomForest 4.7–1.1 (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0210" id="c0215">Liaw and Wiener 2002</ce:cross-ref>) with 10,000 trees and the sample size based on equal numbers of occurrences and random points and samples chosen with replacement. We ran separate, similar models for adults of each species except that we did not test the effect of canopy cover on mature tree presence.</ce:para>
                        <ce:para id="p0125" view="all">All statistical analyses were conducted in R Studio 2022.12.0 using R 4.2.1 (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0265 b0270" id="r0055">R Core Team 2022; R Studio Team 2022</ce:cross-refs>). We used an analysis of variance (ANOVA) in base R to test for differences in elevation and soil nutrients between <ce:italic>Pinus flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings.</ce:para>
                     </ce:section>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0045" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st065">Results</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:section id="s0050" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st070">Density, size, and spatial distribution</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0130" view="all">Across the 15.6 ha, there were 1,052<ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and 498<ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings (72 seedlings ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> and 34 seedlings ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> respectively) and 861<ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and 705<ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> adults (58 stems ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> and 48 stems ha<ce:sup loc="post">−1</ce:sup> respectively)<ce:italic>.</ce:italic> Adult <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> had a quadratic mean diameter (QMD) of 24.8 cm (DBH range 1.0–142.2 cm) and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> had a QMD of 39.8 cm (DBH range 1.0–131.1 cm) (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0010" id="c0220">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0010"/>; <ce:cross-ref refid="s0105" id="c0225">Table S2</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0135" view="all">Seedlings of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> were more aggregated than expected under complete spatial randomness (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0015" id="c0230">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0015"/>a:b). Seedlings of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> were slightly dispersed around adult <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> 2.0–2.25 m while <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> was aggregated around adult <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> from 0.0 to 2.75 m (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0015" id="c0235">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>c:d). Seedlings of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> were aggregated 0.0–1.5 m around adult <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0015" id="c0240">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>e) while <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings were aggregated 1.0–2.75 m around adult <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0015" id="c0245">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>f). All seedlings and trees were significantly aggregated around deadwood from 0.0 to 10.0 m. <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> seedlings were highly aggregated within 0.0–2.0 m and on the south-southwest aspects (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0020" id="c0250">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0020"/>a; <ce:cross-ref refid="f0015" id="c0255">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>g). In contrast, <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings were highly aggregated within 0.0–2.75 m and on the east aspect of deadwood (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0020" id="c0260">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>b; <ce:cross-ref refid="f0015" id="c0265">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>h). The diameter of deadwood had little influence on the distance of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> seedlings from deadwood (R<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup> = 0.01; p &lt; 0.001), and did not influence <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings (p = 0.731; <ce:cross-ref refid="s0105" id="c0270">Fig. S1</ce:cross-ref>). Adult trees were aggregated around deadwood (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0015" id="c0275">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>i:j), but seedlings of both species were significantly more aggregated at distances &lt; 2.5 m than mature conspecific trees (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0015" id="c0280">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>k:l).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0055" view="all">
                     <ce:label>3.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st075">Habitat characteristics of seedlings and adults</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0140" view="all">Proximity to deadwood, conspecific adults, and soil nutrients explained the most variation in seedling occurrence (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0025" id="c0285">Fig. 5</ce:cross-ref>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0025"/>a:b). For <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic>, proximity to deadwood and mature <ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic> were the most important factors in predicting seedling occurrence. Of lesser importance were abiotic and edaphic characteristics such as elevation and soil nutrients. For <ce:italic>P. longaeva,</ce:italic> the most important variables were soil pH, proximity to mature <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic>, and potassium. For both seedling species, proximity to non-<ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic> trees was of low importance along with canopy cover. For adult trees, proximity to mature con-specific trees was the most important delineating feature of habitat followed by proximity to deadwood (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0025" id="c0290">Figs. 5</ce:cross-ref>c:d and <ce:cross-ref id="optpWMssE8hDa" refid="f0030">6</ce:cross-ref>). The topographic wetness index was of greater importance to mature trees than seedlings, while elevation was less important for mature tree habitat. Seedlings of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> occurred at an average of 12 m higher elevation than <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> (p &lt; 0.001), but neither differed from their respective adult populations (<ce:cross-ref refid="f0035" id="c0295">Fig. 7</ce:cross-ref>).<ce:float-anchor refid="f0030"/>
                        <ce:float-anchor refid="f0035"/>
                     </ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0060" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st080">Discussion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0145" view="all">From seedling to old-growth, the defining habitat characteristics of both <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> varied little, but were related to proximity to nearby deadwood and conspecific adults. Patterns of aggregation in seedlings were stronger in <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> than for <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic>, but tree neighborhoods influenced both species from seedling to adult stages.</ce:para>
                  <ce:section id="s0065" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.1</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st085">Facilitation or seed dispersal? Seedling aggregation around adult conspecific trees</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0150" view="all">The aggregation of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> around mature trees is likely a result of a combination of seed dispersal by conspecifics, caching by <ce:italic>N. columbiana</ce:italic> and rodents, and facilitation by mature trees. Direct and animal-mediated seed dispersal likely promote germination of seedlings from 0 to 10 m, with local microsite conditions driving long-term survival of seedlings. The proximity of non-<ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic> trees was a poor predictor of seedling occurrence, which suggests that <ce:italic>N. columbiana</ce:italic> or rodent caching of seeds near trees alone is not the primary mechanism governing seedling spatial patterns. Because seedling habitat preferences differed, particularly with soil nutrients and location around deadwood (<ce:cross-ref id="optkIiWFNRk06" refid="t0005">Table 1</ce:cross-ref>, <ce:cross-ref refid="s0105" id="c0305">Table S2</ce:cross-ref>), there is likely little direct competition for microsites. In a survey of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings across the Great Basin, <ce:cross-ref refid="b0145" id="c0310">Hankin and Bisbing (2021)</ce:cross-ref> found positive associations between trees per hectare and <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> seedlings and the opposite for <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic>. In contrast, we found that <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings were aggregated around mature conspecific at close distances, and <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> was slightly dispersed around conspecific mature trees. Though, <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> established at greater distances from deadwood, potentially indicating lower shade tolerance than <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic>, a finding that agrees with models indicating that shrub and tree cover may reduce <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> recruitment (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0145" id="c0315">Hankin and Bisbing 2021</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0155" view="all">Belowground facultative and <ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic>-specific processes are likely underlying a portion of the seedling habitat requirements. Previous work at the UFDP identified a small pool of shared, root-associated mycorrhizal fungi that exist on both mature <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> roots and a larger, <ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic>-species specific fungal community within the soil (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0040" id="c0320">Birch et al. 2021</ce:cross-ref>). Mature <ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic> may provide a source for beneficial fungal innocula or a connection for a common mycorrhizal network. While much of these communities’ function is unknown, they are a plausible source for the belowground facilitation between the species. The extent of symbiotic fungal communities extends to 16.1 m (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0050" id="c0325">Birch et al. 2023</ce:cross-ref>), indicating that even distant seedlings may benefit from symbiotic fungal innocula, though many fungi have hyphae that extend over scales of only centimeters to several meters (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0215 b0005" id="r0060">Lilleskov et al. 2004; Agerer 2006</ce:cross-refs>) - the spatial scale with the strongest autocorrelation.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0160" view="all">Because direct and animal-mediated seed dispersal are likely to aggregate seeds around mature trees, we cannot parse the mechanisms responsible for seedling aggregation around trees. However, the similarity of seedling-associated patterns in adult populations suggests that negative density-dependent mortality is a weakly operating process for <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> at the UFDP.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0070" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.2</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st090">Deadwood: The importance of proximity and direction in seedling aggregation around logs</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0165" view="all">Seedlings and mature trees of both species were highly aggregated at close distances (0–2.5 m) to deadwood, likely indicating that deadwood modifies local environmental stressors. Deadwood operates as ‘nurse-logs’ in many forests worldwide, reducing competition (<ce:cross-refs refid="b0150 b0285" id="r0065">Harmon and Franklin 1989; Sanchez et al. 2009</ce:cross-refs>), providing physical protection and shade (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0240" id="c0330">Maher et al. 2015</ce:cross-ref>), or alteration of microbial communities (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0130" id="c0335">Fukasawa 2012</ce:cross-ref>). At the UFDP, <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> was, on average, closer to deadwood than <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> and preferentially located on the sun-exposed south-southwest aspect of deadwood. In contrast, <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> seedlings were overwhelmingly located on the shaded east aspects of deadwood, and at greater distances, likely indicating higher drought susceptibility and greater tolerance of light limitation. <ce:cross-ref refid="b0085" id="c0340">Coop and Schoettle (2009)</ce:cross-ref> found that proximity to nearby objects, such as deadwood, promoted <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. aristata</ce:italic> (Rocky Mountain bristlecone pine) establishment out to at least 0.5 m in the Colorado Rocky Mountains. In comparison, we found significant aggregation out to approximately 10.0 m, with significant aggregation occurring between 0.0 and 2.75 m. The diameter of deadwood was poorly correlated with distance to seedlings, likely due to low replication at very large and small deadwood sizes.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0170" view="all">The aggregation around deadwood suggests positive feedback loops where mature trees (especially <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic>) produce long-residence deadwood that promotes the establishment and persistence of new seedlings of both <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic>. Although wildfires may conceivably disrupt this relationship by consuming deadwood, the long fire-return interval and sporadic fuel loading (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0230" id="c0345">Lutz et al. 2021</ce:cross-ref>; <ce:cross-ref refid="s0105" id="c0350">Fig. S2</ce:cross-ref>) likely result in low negative feedbacks between deadwood and tree persistence. The oldest dated deadwood within the UFDP had an outer growth ring of 8 AD, while most sampled <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> deadwood date from the 2nd–12th century. Although <ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic> sp. were relatively minor contributors to mapped deadwood, they have the longest persistence and are abundant in those areas with abundant <ce:italic>Pinus</ce:italic> seedling regeneration.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0175" view="all">The outbreak of <ce:italic>Dendroctonus rufipennis</ce:italic> Kirby (spruce bark beetle) in the 1990s resulted in widespread mortality of <ce:italic>P. engelmannii</ce:italic> in the forests surrounding the UFDP and has resulted in the extensive deposition of deadwood (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0100" id="c0355">DeRose et al. 2012</ce:cross-ref>). A combination of reduced competition and prevalence of deadwood may have stimulated a recruitment pulse at the UFDP. However, a longer timeframe is needed to identify if the current population of 1,500 seedlings represents a departure from historical norms or if mature <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> will begin to be overtaken by co-occurring conifers (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0105" id="c0360">Donnegan and Rebertus 1999</ce:cross-ref>).</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0075" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.3</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st095">Management implications and directions for future research</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0180" view="all">The importance of deadwood proximity to the establishment of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> suggests that preserving existing deadwood may be helpful for seedling establishment. Further, both species were aggregated around adults, highlighting that the conservation of existing mature <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> may be critical for promoting new cohort establishment. Given the extraordinary longevity of some deadwood in five-needle pine ecosystems (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0280" id="c0365">Salzer et al. 2019</ce:cross-ref>), a single piece of deadwood may facilitate multiple cohorts of trees for centuries or millennia. Disturbances such as wildfires that damage or partially consume deadwood and mature trees may pose a challenge (<ce:cross-ref refid="b0095" id="c0370">Dawe et al. 2020</ce:cross-ref>) and require artificial structures or microbial inoculation to mimic some of the benefits provided by deadwood and mature trees.</ce:para>
                     <ce:para id="p0185" view="all">Our study was conducted in a diverse mixed-conifer forest (<ce:cross-ref refid="s0105" id="c0375">Fig. S1</ce:cross-ref>), and the habitat requirements of <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic> and <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic> likely differ markedly from drier, higher-elevation sites such as the White Mountains of California, USA. Future research incorporating more explicit mapping of deadwood, seedlings, and mature trees over large spatial extents will identify patterns of competition and facilitation at intermediate distances (ex. greater than 3.0 m) at other locations and define range-wide patterns. Our seedlings did not include 1st-year germinates, which likely better represent patterns of seedling dispersal. By the time seedlings within the UFDP are mapped, many 1st-year seedlings have likely perished after germinating in unfavorable microsites. Future work disentangling 1st-year dispersal patterns from surviving germinates may address the roles of environmental facilitation and seedling dispersal.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
                  <ce:section id="s0080" view="all">
                     <ce:label>4.4</ce:label>
                     <ce:section-title id="st100">Conclusion</ce:section-title>
                     <ce:para id="p0190" view="all">In a high-elevation, old-growth forest we found that proximity to deadwood and conspecific adults dominates spatial patterns. Soil nutrients, including manganese, pH, and potassium were important in defining the habitat of <ce:italic>P. longaeva</ce:italic>, and to a lesser extent, <ce:italic>P. flexilis</ce:italic>. Our work demonstrates the utility of explicitly mapping seedlings and deadwood to characterize spatial patterns of establishment at intermediate to large distances. Future research on the mechanisms underlying aggregation around deadwood and heterospecific adults will help restore and conserve these vulnerable, magnificent trees.</ce:para>
                  </ce:section>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0085" view="all">
                  <ce:label>5</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st105">Data accessibility statement</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0195" view="all">Data is archived with the Smithsonian institution at <ce:inter-ref xlink:href="https://forestgeo.si.edu" xlink:type="simple" id="ir005">https://forestgeo.si.edu</ce:inter-ref>.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="s0095" view="all">
                  <ce:section-title id="st115">CRediT authorship contribution statement</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0205" view="all">
                     <ce:bold>Joseph D. Birch:</ce:bold> Conceptualization, Methodology, Writing – original draft, Writing – review &amp; editing, Visualization, Formal analysis, Software. <ce:bold>James A. Lutz:</ce:bold> Conceptualization, Data curation, Resources, Writing – original draft, Writing – review &amp; editing, Supervision, Project administration, Funding acquisition.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:sections>
            <ce:conflict-of-interest id="coi005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="st086">Declaration of Competing Interest</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0295" view="all">The authors declare the following financial interests/personal relationships which may be considered as potential competing interests: James Lutz reports financial support was provided by Utah Agricultural Experiment Station.</ce:para>
            </ce:conflict-of-interest>
            <ce:acknowledgment id="ak005" view="all">
               <ce:section-title id="st125">Acknowledgments</ce:section-title>
               <ce:para id="p0215" view="all">This work was conducted under annual research permits from the National Park Service for study CEBR-00016. We thank the managers and staff of Cedar Breaks National Monument for logistical support, especially the hot showers. We thank the students, field crews, and volunteers for surveying, tree mapping, demography survey, and data entry. We thank NS. Birch, LM. Birch, and TFNSA for their support with field logistics. This research was supported by the Utah Agricultural Experiment Station, Utah State University, as journal paper #9669.</ce:para>
            </ce:acknowledgment>
            <ce:appendices view="all">
               <ce:section view="compact-standard" id="s0100">
                  <ce:label>Appendix A</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st130">Supplementary material</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0220" view="all">Supplementary data to this article can be found online at <ce:inter-ref xlink:href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.foreco.2023.121049" xlink:type="simple" id="ir010">https://doi.org/10.1016/j.foreco.2023.121049</ce:inter-ref>.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section view="extended" id="s0105">
                  <ce:label>Appendix A</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="st135">Supplementary material</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0225" view="all">The following are the Supplementary data to this article:<ce:display>
                        <ce:e-component id="m0005">
                           <ce:label>Supplementary data 1</ce:label>
                           <ce:link locator="mmc1" xlink:type="simple" xlink:role="http://data.elsevier.com/vocabulary/ElsevierContentTypes/46.1" xlink:href="pii:S0378112723002839/mmc1" id="lk00040"/>
                        </ce:e-component>
                     </ce:display>
                  </ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:appendices>
